# 6. Skill Extraction Strategy

## 6.1 Start with Dictionary-Based Extraction

Do not begin with LLM extraction. It adds cost, latency, and inconsistency.

Create a preset skill dictionary:

```ts
const skills = [
  { name: "Python", aliases: ["python", "py"] },
  { name: "React", aliases: ["react", "react.js", "reactjs"] },
  { name: "SQL", aliases: ["sql", "mysql", "postgresql", "postgres"] },
  { name: "Excel", aliases: ["excel", "microsoft excel", "ms excel"] },
  { name: "Git", aliases: ["git", "github", "version control"] },
]
```

For each job post:

1. Lowercase text.
2. Match aliases using word boundaries.
3. Save evidence sentence.
4. Mark confidence as high for exact alias matches.

This is simple, explainable, and demo-safe.

---

## 6.2 Skill Importance Scoring

Not all skill mentions are equal.

Use rules:

| Evidence | Requirement Type | Importance |
|---|---|---:|
| “Must have Python” | required | 5 |
| “Required: SQL” | required | 5 |
| “Experience with React” | required | 4 |
| “Good to have Docker” | preferred | 2 |
| Mentioned only in responsibilities | inferred | 1 |

This lets your matching avoid shallow keyword overlap.

---

## 6.3 Later: LLM-Assisted Extraction

After MVP, add a `Job Intelligence Agent` in `lib/agents/job-intelligence.ts`.

It can take raw job description and return:

```json
{
  "role": "Junior Data Analyst",
  "required_skills": ["Excel", "SQL", "Power BI"],
  "preferred_skills": ["Python"],
  "experience_level": "entry",
  "salary_range": [30000, 60000],
  "confidence": 0.88
}
```

But LLM output should enrich, not replace, deterministic extraction.

