# 3. Key Product Principles

## 3.1 “Almost fully aligned”, not weak partial matching

You specifically said:

> not partially, rather almost fully aligned

So the system should avoid showing low-quality matches.

Recommended thresholds:

| Match level | Score | UI behavior |
|---|---:|---|
| Strong match | 85–100% | Show as “Ready to apply” |
| Near-ready | 70–84% | Show as “Almost ready” with gaps |
| Learning path match | 50–69% | Show only in “Future opportunities” |
| Weak match | <50% | Hide from learner by default |

For course completion screens, only show:

- **Strong match**, and
- selected **Near-ready** jobs.

This keeps learner trust high.

## 3.2 Explainability over magic

Every percentage must be explainable.

Bad:

> “You are 82% matched.”

Good:

> “You match 9 of 11 required skills. Required skills carry 80% of the score. Preferred skills carry 20%.”

## 3.3 Market data should inform curriculum, not blindly control it

The scraper should not automatically change courses. It should create signals for admin/curriculum review.

Example:

> “Power BI demand rose 31% across Data Analyst roles. Suggested action: add Power BI module to Data Science track.”

## 3.4 Bangladesh-first taxonomy

Do not only optimize for global tech roles. Bangladesh job boards contain many hybrid roles:

- Executive, IT
- MIS Officer
- Data Entry Operator
- Digital Marketing Executive
- Customer Support + Excel
- Junior Software Engineer
- WordPress Developer
- SEO Specialist
- Office Assistant with MS Office

These roles matter for your target learners.

