# 6. Skill Extraction Strategy

Start simple. Scale later.

## Phase 1 extraction — deterministic keyword matching

For buildfest/demo, use a curated keyword dictionary.

Example:

```python
SKILL_ALIASES = {
  "python": ["python", "django", "flask", "pandas", "numpy"],
  "react": ["react", "react.js", "reactjs", "next.js"],
  "excel": ["excel", "ms excel", "spreadsheet", "vlookup", "pivot table"],
  "sql": ["sql", "mysql", "postgresql", "database query"],
}
```

Pros:

- fast,
- explainable,
- no LLM cost,
- good for demo.

Cons:

- misses ambiguous requirements,
- weaker for Bengali/English mixed posts.

## Phase 2 extraction — LLM-assisted structured extraction

Later, after scraping the page text, call Gemini/Groq only on selected posts.

Prompt output:

```json
{
  "role": "Data Analyst",
  "level": "junior",
  "required_skills": ["Excel", "SQL", "Python"],
  "preferred_skills": ["Power BI"],
  "tools": ["Google Sheets", "Tableau"],
  "experience_years_min": 0,
  "salary_min_bdt": 30000,
  "salary_max_bdt": 60000
}
```

Use LLM only after keyword pass to reduce cost.

## Phase 3 extraction — hybrid confidence scoring

Combine:

- exact keyword match,
- alias match,
- section-aware weighting,
- LLM extraction,
- admin corrections.

Example weighting:

| Signal | Confidence |
|---|---:|
| Skill appears in “Requirements” section | 0.95 |
| Skill appears in title | 0.90 |
| Skill appears in description | 0.70 |
| LLM extracted skill | 0.80 |
| Only related alias found | 0.60 |

